@node Recommendations for Language Designers
@chapter Recommendations for Language Designers

In this chapter I widen the scope, and discuss properties of FSet that I think would have value in
other languages as well.  I then move on to critiques of libraries for other languages, from an FSet
perspective.

@hrule{}

@node Features of FSet
@section Features of FSet

One thing I've tried to do in FSet is to choose names for functional update operations carefully.  I
recall reading once about newcomers to Java trying to use its @code{BigInteger} class, which is
functional.  They tended to expect an expression @code{x.add(y)} to mutate @code{x} to contain the
sum, when it returns the sum instead.  I contend that naming the operation @code{plus} instead of
@code{add} would have largely prevented this confusion; people have written @code{x + y} since they
were children in school, and no one thinks of that as somehow changing the value of @code{x},
whatever that would even mean in a mathematical context.  (Java doesn't support operator
overloading, so literally making @code{x + y} work on @code{BigInteger} was not an available option;
@code{x.plus(y)} is the closest one could get.)

Two important operations in FSet are named @code{with} and @code{less}; @code{with} adds an element
or pair to a collection, while @code{less} removes one.  These names come from SETL.  Like
@code{plus}, they are prepositions.

Naming things is always a matter of tradeoffs.  Good names make code understandable by carrying the
right connotations, but names also need to be reasonably familiar words, and for common operations,
not too long.  I wouldn't go so far as to say that all functional update operations should be named
by prepositions, but I do think that, other things being equal, prepositions and nouns tend to be
better choices than verbs, and verbs that don't connote mutation are better than those that do.  In
a couple of cases, where the obvious names @code{insert} and @code{splice} strongly connote
mutation, I have used their past participles (@code{inserted} and @code{spliced}) instead of their
base forms.  (Honesty compels me to admit that this is a recent change; I have not, historically,
adhered to my own desideratum as well as I would have liked.  But I still recommend it.)

Here are some other functional collections libraries and the names they use for operations like
@code{with} and @code{less}:

@multitable @columnfractions .12 .25 .25 .2
@item @b{Library} @tab @b{@code{with}} (on sets/on maps) @tab @b{@code{less}} (on sets/on maps) @tab @b{notes}
@item Clojure core @tab @code{conj} / @code{assoc} @tab @code{disj} / @code{dissoc}
@item Racket @tab @code{hash-set} @tab @code{hash-remove} @tab 1
@item Scala @tab @code{incl} / @code{updated} @tab @code{excl} / @code{removed} @tab 2
@item Haskell @tab @code{insert} @tab @code{delete} @tab 3
@item SML/NJ @tab @code{add} / @code{insert} @tab @code{subtract} / @code{remove}
@item Pyrsistent (Python) @tab @code{add} / @code{set} @tab @code{remove}
@item RPDS (Rust) @tab @code{insert} @tab @code{remove}
@end multitable

Notes:

@enumerate
@item @ilc{1}
Only maps (hash tables) are provided.  Racket uses the popular Scheme convention that names of
mutating operations end in @code{!}; someone familiar with that convention should be able to guess
that these are functional updates.
@item @ilc{2}
Here we see a use of past participles.
@item @ilc{3}
Of course, there's no ambiguity here since anyone writing Haskell knows it's a pure functional language.
@end enumerate

A lot of these sound to me like verbs of mutation, with Clojure and Scala being the two languages
that seem to have gone to some effort to avoid those.

Another area where I would hold FSet up as an example is space efficiency.  I wanted to support
client programs that use many small collection instances, as well as those that use large
collections.  Two things I have done to reduce space overhead are:

@itemize
@item
It's not uncommon for people to implement maps first, then reuse the implementation for sets, by
wrapping it with a set API that uses only the map key slots; the value slots are still allocated,
but don't contain anything important.  FSet sets are implemented separately from maps, so they don't
waste this space.
@item
The WB-tree implementations, including that of seqs, use heterogeneous trees: instead of having tree
nodes all the way down to the leaves, they keep the lowest two to four levels of the tree in
bounded-length vectors.  This saves a lot of space on small collections; for example, an 8-element
set made entirely of tree nodes would take an estimated 37 words, but in FSet, it's just 11 words.
@end itemize

FSet has several semantic features that I would recommend to language and library designers:

@itemize
@item
@href{Map and Seq Defaults, Defaults} associated with maps and seqs.  This not a difficult feature
to add; the only complications show up in operations like @href{Method map-union (map map),
@code{map-union}} that arguably need to do something sensible with the defaults of their operands
(though, simply ignoring them might be a viable option).
@item
@href{Quasi-Mutating Operators, Quasi-mutating operators}, on the other hand, are likely to require
language support; few languages are designed in such a way that they could be added as a library.
@item
@href{Bags, Bags}, though not as commonly used as maps or sets, are still handy often enough to
deserve inclusion in a comprehensive collections library.  Although these can be implemented as just
a wrapper around maps, FSet has separate implementations for them, so as to be able to track both
the bag size (the total of the multiplicities) and the set size (the number of unique elements) for
every subtree.
@item
@href{Binary Relations, Binary relations} are another type that are useful enough to be worth
implementing.
@item
@href{Left Preference, Left preference} is a property of operations such as @href{Method union (set
set), @code{union}} that combine two collections into a third in some way.  It says that when the
two operands contain distinct objects that are nonetheless equal according to the applicable
comparison function, and one of those objects is used in the result, the one in the result will
always be the one that came from the left operand.  The Haskell library also makes this guarantee.
@item
Allowing comparison functions to implement a @href{Strict Weak Orderings, strict weak ordering},
instead of requiring (or at least assuming) a total ordering, is perhaps a more controversial design
choice.  There is a small amount of overhead associated with allowing for the possibility of
equivalent-but-unequal elements; the feature is not completely free.  For Common Lisp, it is
arguably a necessity, if only because of the admittedly rare case of uninterned symbols with the
same name (but I have seen macros generate such symbols in the wild; the concern is not academic).
In other languages, you (or rather, your users) can probably live without it the vast majority of
the time, but I wonder whether there might not be rare exceptions.  None of the other ordered-tree
collections implementations I have looked at allow strict weak orderings, though.
@end itemize

